To provide a more relevant example, let's take the problem of calculating the Fibonacci sequence. 

The Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers where a number is the sum of the two preceding ones, usually starting with 0 and 1.

Here's a recursive function in JavaScript to calculate the nth Fibonacci number:

```javascript
function fibonacci(n) {
  if (n === 0) {
    return 0; // base case
  } else if (n === 1) {
    return 1; // base case
  } else {
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2); // recursive call
  }
}

console.log(fibonacci(10)); // prints the 10th Fibonacci number
```

This function works by recursively calling itself to calculate the nth Fibonacci number. However, as the recursion depth increases, this function can become inefficient due to repeated calculations. A more efficient approach would be to use dynamic programming to store the results of previous calculations.
